# {"source": "IPSO ruling, Lancashire Telegraph school-attack story (single anonymous source); Editors' Code Clause 1 (Accuracy)", "article": "A teacher at Queen Elizabeth's Grammar School was attacked by a pupil wielding a knife in a classroom last week, leaving staff terrified, according to a parent who contacted this newspaper anonymously. The school has not commented.", "critiques": [{"agent": "legal_skeptic", "text_quote": "was attacked by a pupil wielding a knife in a classroom", "span": [46, 101], "issue_label": "single anonymous source as fact", "question": "This is a serious, specific allegation and the only thing holding it up is one anonymous parent who emailed us. We have not put it to the school, and 'has not commented' may just mean we did not ask properly. If the parent is wrong, or carrying a grudge, what is left?", "why_it_matters": "IPSO upheld a breach against the Lancashire Telegraph for almost exactly this: an attack story built on a single anonymous source, stated as established fact, not properly put to the school before publication.", "fix_suggestion": "Get a second source, a staff member, another parent, a police log, or attribute the whole account to the parent and label it unverified. Then put the specific allegation to the school with real time to respond, and say in the piece what we asked and when.", "replacement": "was attacked by a pupil, according to a parent who contacted this newspaper, an account the school has not yet confirmed", "severity": "high"}]}
# {"source": "IPSO ruling 00370-24, Hewitt v Belfast Telegraph (unproven allegations not flagged as unproven)", "article": "Three sources have told the Belfast Telegraph that Mr Hewitt repeatedly harassed neighbours and circulated confidential police records around the estate, the paper reports.", "critiques": [{"agent": "legal_skeptic", "text_quote": "Mr Hewitt repeatedly harassed neighbours and circulated confidential police records", "span": [51, 134], "issue_label": "unproven allegations stated as fact", "question": "Three sources is plural, which is good. But none of these claims have been tested in court or by an investigation. We are stating them flatly, without making clear they are unproven allegations. Is the reader being told the difference?", "why_it_matters": "IPSO upheld a breach against the Belfast Telegraph for serious allegations sourced to anonymous people but presented as established fact. Newsrooms can report allegations; we have to label them as allegations.", "fix_suggestion": "Frame the claims as allegations from the sources, not as findings. 'Three sources alleged that...' with a clear note that the allegations have not been tested. If we have documents, lean on them; if we do not, the labelling has to do the work.", "replacement": "Three sources have told the Belfast Telegraph that Mr Hewitt allegedly harassed neighbours and circulated what they say were confidential police records", "severity": "high"}]}
{"source": "IPSO rulings on anonymous single-source claims presented as fact; Editors' Code Clause 1", "article": "The council's finance director took payments from a contractor in exchange for steering a 2 million pound waste contract, sources said.", "critiques": [{"agent": "legal_skeptic", "text_quote": "took payments from a contractor in exchange for steering a 2 million pound waste contract", "span": [31, 120], "issue_label": "bribery alleged as fact", "question": "'Took payments in exchange for steering a contract' describes bribery, a crime. We state it as fact and hang it on 'sources' with nothing else visible. Do we have the payment records, a named second source, an audit?", "why_it_matters": "IPSO has repeatedly ruled that presenting an anonymous source's claim as fact rather than clearly as a claim breaches the accuracy clause. For a criminal allegation against a named official it is also the core fact pattern of a libel suit.", "fix_suggestion": "Attribute it plainly and soften the verb until we can prove intent. Keep whatever documentary evidence we have in the file in case we have to defend it.", "replacement": "is alleged by sources to have accepted payments from a contractor that later won a 2 million pound waste contract", "severity": "high"}]}
# {"source": "Editors' Code Clause 1 (Accuracy); standard pre-publication defamation review", "article": "City councilman Mark Reyes stole more than 400,000 dollars from a youth sports nonprofit he chaired, according to a former board member.", "critiques": [{"agent": "legal_skeptic", "text_quote": "stole more than 400,000 dollars", "span": [27, 58], "issue_label": "criminal verb without a charge", "question": "'Stole' is theft, a specific crime with specific elements. Do we have an indictment, a civil judgment, or an audit? A former board member's account, even an honest one, is not a finding.", "why_it_matters": "Stating as fact that a named person committed a crime, with no charge and one source, is textbook defamation per se. The verb is the first thing opposing counsel circles.", "fix_suggestion": "Soften the verb to what we can defend and attribute it. If we hold the audit, anchor the number to the audit instead of pinning the verb on the person.", "replacement": "is alleged to have diverted more than 400,000 dollars", "severity": "high"}]}
# {"source": "Editors' Code Clause 1; standard pre-publication defamation review", "article": "Documents obtained by the Herald show hospital administrator Susan Kemp defrauded Medicare through a billing scheme that prosecutors are now investigating.", "critiques": [{"agent": "legal_skeptic", "text_quote": "defrauded Medicare through a billing scheme", "span": [72, 115], "issue_label": "conviction asserted before a charge", "question": "The same sentence says prosecutors are still investigating, which means no charge has been filed. But we have already used 'defrauded', the conclusion a court has not reached. Which is it?", "why_it_matters": "Stating that a named person committed fraud during an open investigation, before any charge, is one of the most common ways newsrooms get sued and lose. An investigation is not a finding.", "fix_suggestion": "Report the investigation, not the verdict. Save 'defrauded' for after an indictment or judgment, and attribute it to that document when it lands.", "replacement": "is under federal investigation over a Medicare billing scheme", "severity": "high"}]}
{"source": "Editors' Code Clause 1 and right-of-reply practice", "article": "The investigation found that Detective James Cole pressured at least three witnesses to change their statements. Cole could not be reached for comment.", "critiques": [{"agent": "legal_skeptic", "text_quote": "Cole could not be reached for comment", "span": [113, 150], "issue_label": "thin right of reply on a serious allegation", "question": "We are accusing a named former officer of witness tampering, and his entire right of reply is five words. What did we actually try, and over how long?", "why_it_matters": "The Editors' Code requires a fair opportunity to reply to significant allegations. 'Could not be reached', with no detail, is the line that makes a regulator or a court conclude we did the minimum.", "fix_suggestion": "Document the outreach inside the article: the channels tried and the time window. If we genuinely could not reach him, say exactly what we did so the effort is on the record.", "replacement": "Cole did not respond to messages left with his lawyer and at two phone numbers over eight days", "severity": "medium"}]}
{"source": "Editors' Code Clause 1; defamation review on opinion stated as fact", "article": "Internal emails show the chief executive ordered staff to delete the test records, a clear cover-up of the safety failures.", "critiques": [{"agent": "legal_skeptic", "text_quote": "a clear cover-up of the safety failures", "span": [83, 122], "issue_label": "our characterization stated as fact", "question": "'A clear cover-up of the safety failures' is a conclusion, not something the emails say. No regulator has found a cover-up. We have. Are we ready to defend that as our own assertion?", "why_it_matters": "Calling a named executive's conduct a cover-up in our own voice turns a description into a legal conclusion we then have to prove. Attributing it, or describing the conduct plainly, keeps the protection.", "fix_suggestion": "Describe what the emails actually show and let the reader draw the inference, or attribute the word 'cover-up' to a named source who will stand behind it.", "replacement": "which former staff describe as an attempt to bury the safety failures", "severity": "medium"}]}
{"source": "Editors' Code Clause 1; defamation review on paraphrase escalation", "article": "The whistleblower said the agency 'wasn't careful' with the figures. In other words, the agency falsified its budget reports.", "critiques": [{"agent": "legal_skeptic", "text_quote": "In other words, the agency falsified its budget reports", "span": [69, 124], "issue_label": "paraphrase escalates the source's claim", "question": "The source said 'wasn't careful'. We have translated that into 'falsified', which is a deliberate act and a far stronger, far riskier claim. Did the source actually say falsification, or did we upgrade it?", "why_it_matters": "Turning a hedged claim into a definite accusation is a libel exposure we manufactured ourselves. If sued, we cannot fall back on the source, because the source never said it.", "fix_suggestion": "Quote the source's actual words and let them stand, or go back and get the source to say on the record whether they mean deliberate falsification.", "replacement": "The whistleblower said the agency 'wasn't careful' with the figures", "severity": "high"}]}
{"source": "IPSO guidance on anonymous sourcing; defamation review on source independence", "article": "According to two people with knowledge of the matter, the director knew about the defect, hid it from regulators, and lied to the board.", "critiques": [{"agent": "legal_skeptic", "text_quote": "the director knew about the defect, hid it from regulators, and lied to the board", "span": [54, 135], "issue_label": "one sourcing line carrying three allegations", "question": "Three separate and serious claims are all riding on the same 'two people with knowledge'. Is each claim sourced to both people, or is each person good for one piece of it? If those two turn out to be the same circle, the whole paragraph is single-sourced.", "why_it_matters": "Stacking multiple distinct allegations behind one anonymous attribution means one recantation collapses everything. For libel purposes, two sources from the same room are close to one source.", "fix_suggestion": "Separate the claims and show what supports each one. Keep the best-sourced allegation now, and hold the others until they are independently confirmed.", "replacement": null, "severity": "high"}]}
{"source": "Defamation by implication / juxtaposition; standard pre-publication review", "article": "City Hall awarded the contract to Walsh Construction. The firm is owned by Frank Walsh, who lives three doors down from the mayor's mother.", "critiques": [{"agent": "legal_skeptic", "text_quote": "lives three doors down from the mayor's mother", "span": [92, 138], "issue_label": "innuendo by juxtaposition", "question": "We have put the contract award and the geography of the owner's house in the same paragraph and trusted the reader to assume a connection. If there is no proof the proximity matters to the contract, this is innuendo. If there is proof, where is it?", "why_it_matters": "Defamation by implication does not require a direct claim. Placing two facts side by side so the reader infers wrongdoing is enough for a suit. UK and US courts have both ruled against publishers on this pattern.", "fix_suggestion": "Either prove the connection (donations, calls between the families, meetings on this contract) and report it directly, or strike the geography line. Innuendo we cannot defend is worse than no story.", "replacement": null, "severity": "high"}]}
{"source": "UK Contempt of Court Act 1981 and US guidance on pre-trial publicity", "article": "Robert Lane, who is awaiting trial next month on murder charges, has a long history of violent outbursts, three former colleagues said.", "critiques": [{"agent": "legal_skeptic", "text_quote": "has a long history of violent outbursts", "span": [65, 104], "issue_label": "prejudicial material on an awaiting-trial defendant", "question": "Mr Lane is awaiting trial. We are publishing colleagues' character claims about his violent history right next to his charges. Even if everything we have is true, this is exactly the material the Contempt of Court Act is designed to keep out of public view during active proceedings.", "why_it_matters": "Publishing character-evidence-style material about a defendant during active criminal proceedings risks contempt of court in the UK and a successful motion to change venue or strike the jury pool in the US. It can collapse the trial.", "fix_suggestion": "Hold the colleague accounts until the trial is over or the jury is sequestered. Report the charges and the next court date, and save the background reporting for after a verdict.", "replacement": null, "severity": "high"}]}
# {"source": "Defamation review: the slide-deck example of 'colluded' without a signed document", "article": "Emails show the chief executive colluded with the lobbyist to draft the legislation in his client's favour.", "critiques": [{"agent": "legal_skeptic", "text_quote": "colluded with the lobbyist to draft the legislation", "span": [32, 83], "issue_label": "criminal verb without a signed agreement", "question": "'Colluded' means a covert agreement, often with criminal overtones. Do the emails actually show an agreement, or do they show coordination, communication, exchange of drafts? Those are different verbs and different exposures.", "why_it_matters": "'Colluded' is one of a small set of verbs that automatically signal wrongdoing to a reader and to a judge. Without a signed agreement or a second source confirming the agreement, we are reaching past the evidence.", "fix_suggestion": "Use the weakest verb the evidence supports. If the emails show drafting back and forth, 'coordinated', 'communicated', or 'worked with' carry the same descriptive load with none of the legal weight.", "replacement": "coordinated with the lobbyist on drafts of the legislation that favoured his client", "severity": "high"}]}
{"source": "Defamation review: 'lied' as a state-of-mind verb requiring proof of intent", "article": "Senator Voss lied about his military service in last week's debate, records show.", "critiques": [{"agent": "legal_skeptic", "text_quote": "Senator Voss lied about his military service", "span": [0, 44], "issue_label": "intent verb without proof of intent", "question": "'Lied' requires not just that the statement was false but that he knew it was false. The records show the statement was inaccurate. Do they show he knew?", "why_it_matters": "'Lied' is a state-of-mind verb. Proving it requires evidence of intent, which a paper trail of his statements rarely supplies by itself. 'Lied' is also the verb a public-figure plaintiff uses to argue actual malice against us.", "fix_suggestion": "Report what the records show and what he said, and let the gap be visible. If we have evidence he knew, lead with it.", "replacement": "Senator Voss's account of his military service was contradicted by records released last week", "severity": "high"}]}
# {"source": "Defamation review: 'fled' as a guilt-implying verb", "article": "Hours after the indictment was unsealed, Anders fled the country on a flight to Lisbon.", "critiques": [{"agent": "legal_skeptic", "text_quote": "fled the country", "span": [48, 64], "issue_label": "guilt-implying verb on a movement", "question": "'Fled' implies he was running from the law. Did he travel on a ticket bought after the indictment, or had this flight been booked for weeks? The verb is doing a lot of work that we may not have evidence to support.", "why_it_matters": "'Fled' frames a routine movement as consciousness of guilt. If the flight was pre-booked or business travel, the framing is inaccurate and is exactly the kind of phrasing a defamation suit can survive on.", "fix_suggestion": "Report the movement neutrally and let the reader weigh the timing. If we have evidence the booking was reactive, say so explicitly.", "replacement": "left the country on a flight to Lisbon hours after the indictment was unsealed", "severity": "medium"}]}
# {"source": "Defamation review: 'linked to' without a defined link", "article": "The senator has been linked to the offshore accounts named in the leaked documents.", "critiques": [{"agent": "legal_skeptic", "text_quote": "has been linked to the offshore accounts", "span": [12, 52], "issue_label": "vague link", "question": "Linked how? The leak names accounts; we have not said whether the senator owns them, signed on them, sent funds to them, or merely shares a name with a beneficial owner. 'Linked to' is the phrase newsrooms reach for when the reporting is not yet clear.", "why_it_matters": "Vague linkage on a serious allegation is a libel-suit invitation, because the reader infers ownership or wrongdoing while the publisher cannot point to a specific finding. The defence becomes 'we never quite said it', which courts dislike.", "fix_suggestion": "Replace 'linked to' with the actual nature of the connection, sourced. If the connection is only that the senator's name appears in a document, say so. If the connection is ownership, name it.", "replacement": "is named in the leaked documents as a signatory on two of the offshore accounts, according to two people who reviewed the files", "severity": "high"}]}
{"source": "Defamation review: 'allegedly' used everywhere as a legal fig leaf", "article": "Brewer allegedly stole from the trust, allegedly hid the funds in offshore accounts, and allegedly threatened his secretary into silence.", "critiques": [{"agent": "legal_skeptic", "text_quote": "Brewer allegedly stole from the trust, allegedly hid the funds in offshore accounts, and allegedly threatened his secretary into silence", "span": [0, 136], "issue_label": "'allegedly' as a blanket shield", "question": "Three serious allegations chained together with three 'allegedly's. The word is doing structural work, but allegedly is not a legal force field. The reader still walks away believing he did all three. Who is making each allegation, and on what evidence?", "why_it_matters": "Courts have repeatedly held that the word 'allegedly' does not by itself protect against defamation when the surrounding text treats the claims as established. We need attributed allegations, not a sprinkling of 'allegedly'.", "fix_suggestion": "Attribute each claim to its source: 'Brewer is alleged to have stolen from the trust, according to the lawsuit filed by the trustees, and the lawsuit also accuses him of hiding the funds and threatening his secretary.'", "replacement": null, "severity": "high"}]}
# {"source": "Pre-publication review: misuse of 'a court heard'", "article": "A court heard yesterday that Mr Patel had been beating his wife for years.", "critiques": [{"agent": "legal_skeptic", "text_quote": "A court heard yesterday that Mr Patel had been beating his wife for years", "span": [0, 73], "issue_label": "courtroom phrase smuggling a claim as fact", "question": "'A court heard' makes this sound like a finding of fact. It is in fact a witness or counsel statement in evidence, which is contested. Was this the prosecution's opening, a witness's testimony, or a cross-examined claim?", "why_it_matters": "Using 'a court heard' to launder an untested allegation into a flat factual claim is a recognised contempt and accuracy risk in court reporting. The reader is misled about whether anything has been established.", "fix_suggestion": "Say exactly what stage of the hearing produced the claim and who made it: 'Prosecutors told the court that...' or 'The complainant testified that...' so the reader understands it is testimony, not finding.", "replacement": "The prosecution told the court yesterday that Mr Patel had beaten his wife for years, an allegation he denies", "severity": "high"}]}
{"source": "Privacy and defamation overlap: identifying suspects pre-charge", "article": "Police searched the home of David Mercer, a 38-year-old accountant, on Tuesday as part of the fraud investigation. No charges have been filed.", "critiques": [{"agent": "legal_skeptic", "text_quote": "David Mercer, a 38-year-old accountant", "span": [28, 66], "issue_label": "naming a pre-charge suspect", "question": "Mercer has not been charged. Naming, photographing, and locating him in a fraud investigation puts him in front of his community with a presumption of guilt the law has not made. Is there a public interest that requires using his name now, before any charge?", "why_it_matters": "UK guidance (College of Policing, Editors' Code, and the Cliff Richard ruling) is that suspects should not normally be identified before charge. The exposure is both privacy and defamation if the investigation closes without action.", "fix_suggestion": "Hold the name until charge unless there is a clear public interest in identifying him now. Report the search and the investigation without the identifier.", "replacement": "Police searched the home of a 38-year-old accountant on Tuesday as part of the fraud investigation", "severity": "high"}]}
# {"source": "Defamation review: off-the-record material used as on-record", "article": "Mason confirmed in a private conversation last week that he had concealed the figures from the auditors.", "critiques": [{"agent": "legal_skeptic", "text_quote": "Mason confirmed in a private conversation last week that he had concealed the figures from the auditors", "span": [0, 103], "issue_label": "off-the-record material used as on-record", "question": "Was the private conversation actually on the record, or are we reporting something said in confidence? If it was off the record, publishing it is both a sourcing breach and an evidentiary problem: the source can deny he ever said it and we are left holding the claim alone.", "why_it_matters": "Off-the-record claims are notoriously hard to defend in libel actions because the source can recant. Newsrooms also tend to lose the source's trust forever after such a move.", "fix_suggestion": "Confirm with the source whether the line was on the record. If not, hold it. If it was, say so plainly: 'In an on-the-record interview, Mason said...'", "replacement": null, "severity": "high"}]}
# {"source": "Defamation review: comparing the subject to a convicted figure", "article": "The mayor's response to the corruption inquiry recalls Richard Nixon at his most evasive.", "critiques": [{"agent": "legal_skeptic", "text_quote": "recalls Richard Nixon at his most evasive", "span": [47, 88], "issue_label": "comparison that imputes guilt", "question": "The Nixon comparison does the work of saying the mayor is engaged in a Watergate-style coverup without us having to prove it. Is the comparison earned by the documented conduct, or are we using it to imply more than we can show?", "why_it_matters": "Rhetorical comparisons to convicted or disgraced figures can constitute defamation by implication where the comparison points the reader to an unproven conclusion. They are also catnip for opposing counsel.", "fix_suggestion": "Drop the comparison and report the documented evasions directly, or attribute the comparison to a named critic who will defend it.", "replacement": "is evasive in ways that critics, including her own former chief of staff, have called Nixonian", "severity": "medium"}]}
{"source": "Editors' Code Clause 1; example of a properly sourced and balanced passage", "article": "Senator Linda Hart voted against the housing bill on Tuesday after receiving more than 200,000 dollars in donations from the real estate lobby over two years, federal disclosure filings show. Hart's office said the vote reflected concerns about zoning preemption.", "critiques": []}
# {"source": "Editors' Code Clause 1 distinction between comment and fact; fair comment", "article": "In my view, the mayor's housing plan is a giveaway to developers dressed up as reform, and voters should see it for what it is. This is an opinion column.", "critiques": []}
# {"source": "Editors' Code Clause 1; example of an on-the-record public figure within their role", "article": "The mayor told reporters at City Hall on Wednesday that she would veto the council's budget, calling it 'fiscally reckless.'", "critiques": []}
{"source": "Example of an allegation attributed to a court filing, fully sourced", "article": "Brewer is accused in a lawsuit filed Tuesday in Cook County of diverting more than 400,000 dollars from the trust, hiding the funds in offshore accounts, and threatening his former secretary into silence. Brewer's lawyer said the claims were 'a fiction' and would be contested at trial.", "critiques": []}
# {"source": "Example of a corruption story sourced to a court ruling, with response", "article": "A federal judge ruled Tuesday that Mason had concealed material figures from the company's auditors in the lead-up to the 2022 restatement, a finding Mason said he would appeal.", "critiques": []}
